![][image1]

This "Dashboard" is the main page displayed after logging in. It features several tabs that provide a concise overview of various system information. This is crucial for the firewall administrator as it offers access to a multitude of configuration options for interacting with and modifying the firewall settings.

![][image2]

The “Device” \> “Services” tab for the Firewall allows the configuration of the DNS and NTP. Configuring DNS on the firewall is essential as it enables the translation of domain names. This is required for policy enforcement and communication with external security resources. NTP ensures time synchronization, this is critical for maintaining the integrity of logs, enforcing time-based control, and validating certificates. 

![][image3]

The “Management Interface Setting” is directly connected to the operations of the firewall. This allows Permitted IP Addresses to connect to the firewall via MGT. This allows administrators to configure or monitor services. A misconfigured management interface setting system wouldn’t allow any of these services to work. 

![][image4]  
The “Commit” process is when an administrator is done making his configurations and is ready to apply the new configurations to the active firewall configuration. The changes made prior before applying “Commit” don’t take into effect until I “commit” them.
